at he\nhoped for prosperity during the com\ning year, said that the results accom\nplished so far had'been small.\nE3. D. Hulbert, vice president of the\nMerchants' Loan Trust company,\npointed out that the fact that manu\nfacturers were inclined to increase the\nworking forces in their plants was\nFormer South Dakotan\nGoes to the Bad\nBrookings Register A. dispatch to\nthe St. Paul Pioneer Prbss from' Los\nAngeles under date of last ^Thursday\ntells of a tragedy In which Arthur\nCunningham, formerly a-resident of\nBrookings, was the chief figure. Cun\nningham formerly lived here with his\nparents, but moved away some years\nago, and his wife is a daughter of J.\nH. Kelsey, a pioneer business man of\nthis county. The dispatch says:\nSeated in the front compartment of\nan automobile, and clasped in each\nother's arms, the bodies of Mrs. Vi8la\nKerr and Arthur E. Cunningham were\nfound on a lonely road at the out\nskirts of Long Beach late last night.\nAfter a desperate struggle, Cunning\nham had shot Mrs. Kerr twice while,\nholding her tight against his breast\nand then had turned the revolver on\nhimself.\nFor more than two hours' the ma\nchine of death stood at the roadside,\nand many persons passed before the\ncrime was discovered\nMrs. Kerr and Cunniu^ha-rS^were-'en\ngaged in the real estate business in\nLong Beach under the Arm name of\ndicating an active business year are: ^el Cunningham...\nThe seeming certainty that the rail-l At the Cunningham home, 1222 Lin\nroads will be granted an advance of! den avenue, sat Mrs Cunningham,\n5 per cent in freight rates. with her four little children, the\nMore plentiful supply oj money and youngest a baby of 9 months, waiting\nlower interest rates tor her husband. Mrs. Cunningham\nComing inauguration of the new sys-l *s\na\ntem of regional reserve banks, which Kelsey,., wealthy, residents\nis counted on \"to make panics impos- apolis. j.\nsible\" \"He killedmrlffive when fte deliber-\nBetter undet-St&uding between buSi-j