t 1 would frighten him\ninto giving her up. I told him that\nI would go to her husband and tell all\nI knew. That night 1 found a loaded\npistol under his pillow. I became\nafraid that he would kill me to pre\nvent me from telling Mr. Kerr. I\n\u2022wrote tc my parents in Minneapolis\ntelling them my fears, and they at\nonce came to,. Long..Peach,t I.wm,.al\nmost\n\"We came to Long Beach two years\nago from Porfland. We formerly\ncame from Aurora, S. D., where we\nwere married. We' had known each\nother since we were children.\n\"I will go home with my parents in\nthe, spring.\" ggP\nKerr, the hus^Sn'd and his twin\nsons, 19 years old, declare they never\nheard a breath of suspicion against\nthe wife and mother. The Kerr fan*\nily also is wealthy.\nBurke Has Not With\ndrawn from Contest\nInformation from Pierre headquar-\none of the best indications of better/ ters indicate that Mr. Crawford awl\nconditions.\n\"Write 'optimism' in blackface type\nclear across the page and you will ex\npress my sentiments,\" said Harry N.\nWheeler, vice president of\nhis managers are getting mighty des\nperate over Mr. Burke's apparent suc\ncess and popularity throughout the\nstate. The Crawford headquarters\nsent broadcast the report that Mr.\nBurke had withdrawn from the sen\natorial race. This report was abso\nlutely, and it would appear, malicious\nly false and shows the desperate\nstraits into which the Crawford cam\npaign has fallen. Mr. Burke, the peo\nple's candidate tor the United States\nsenate. Is in the race-to stay and win.\nis practically conceded now Hjat\nhe .Will be the people's choice on\nMarch 24th to lead the republican\nty to victory in November.\nIS YEARS\nA\nA New Whip for Bad\nHusbands in Wisconsin\nHelf the jails of the the state are\nnedrly empty. They are almost whol\nly empty during the summer months\nwhen outdoor work can be done in a,\ndozen occupations and when farmers\nare clamoring for hands.\nThe way the housewife can bring\nhor recreant husband to terms if he\nis inclined to spend too' much of his\nwages on liquor or other things is to\nwatch her chance to have him arrest\ned for \"disorderly conduct\" or some\nminor charge. The judge sentences\nhim to ninety days' labor. He re\nturns to his old job, but the sheriff\ncollects the wages and turns them all\nover to the wife.\nThere is no getting away from the\nlaw either. If the sheriff be lax he\nis liable to a fine of $100, and if the\nprisoner, working outside of the jail,\n.escapes across the county line he is\nliable to a fine of $500 pr a year in\njail or state prison.\nof Minne-jto aterm of ninety days in jail.. Re\nfusal to work means ten days in soli\ntary confinement on a bread and wa\nter diet. Good work means shorten\ning of the term by a fourth of the\ntime.\nJohn Rabbits are\nhick\nWATEKTOWN, SOUTH DAKOTA, THURSDAY, JANUARY 29,1914\nBrookings Mayor is\nPleased With bice Line\nMadison, Wis., Jan. 28.\u2014Women ofl Mayor JohnBoa of Brookings recent\nWisconsin have a new \"whip\" for bad visited Minneapolis and the Reg\nhuubands. The Huber work law, by'lster \u00b0f that city quotes him on hie\nwhich men charged with offenses return as follows:' \"1 was very favor\nwhich come within the jurisdiction of aMy impressed with what I saw of the\na justice of the peace are put to. work Electric Short Line while at Minne\nand their money turned to those de\npendent upon them,-nicely serves the\npurpose of wives.\napolis last week. I had the pleasure\nof making the flret trip over tlie line\nwith the party of Minneapolis business\nmen,and they alt seemed to be en\nthusiastic about the Bew road and\nwere outspoken of their confidence in\nthe Luces. The road is substantially\nbuilt, with heavy rails and ties and\ndoes not look like tie South Dakota\nCentral. At the luncheon tit the Rad\nisson after the trip Mr. Dayton of the\nDayton department store said: '1\nfeel that it is not just right for us\" to\nbe guests of Mr. Luce at thto lunch\neon, as it seems to me