of\ndistribution. Rabbit, he says, makes\ngood \"eats.\"\u2014Minneapolis Tribune.\nSouth Dakota Fire\nLaw Declared N. G.\n'|s# ..f\u2014\nWashington, Jan,\nDakota law\nfor double the amount of loss sus\ntained by property owners through\nflres originating from locomotives un\nless the loss was paid in full in sixty\ndays was annulled today by the su\nperrae court as violative of tfeS four\nteenth amendment\nWUHffg\nand bakery at 122 north\nMaple street. The new bakery will\nbe known as the Vienna Bakery and\nwill- carry a full line of everything\nmade in the baksry line.\nThe proprietor, Mr. Warady,. has\nhad 'tWenty-twQ. years experience in\nthe bakery business in Germany and\nto put up the\nof 'bukery\nery will flourish and do a Rood bust\nness.\nAI. Farl is Chosen to\nHead Association\n'\u2022\u2022At a meeting of the Retail Liquor\nDealers Association ot the state last\nweek A, Farl, of Watertown, was\nelected president of the association\nThe wholesale riTJTilt Wtlife' r^suft'6f\na hunt by Fort Pierre people in and\naround the alfalfa fields along the\nMissouri river, north-of that town.1 mistake in choosing Mr. Pari for its\nThe alfalfa growers in that part of executive office^.Mr. Far! has resided\nStanley county notified their Port in Watertown tor over thirty yearB\nPierre friends that they needed help and has always been connected with\nin reducing the rabbit crop for the the liquor business during that time\nprotection of their fields, which were' Few men stand higher in business\nsuffering from ravages of the many circles than does Mr. Pari. He is an\nrabbits. About 50 hunters answered exemplary soloon man and adheres to\nThe association certainly made no\nthe laws 'of the state as close as it is\npossible. He is pleasant and courteous\nand -his word is as good as a govern\nment bond. When bis saloon is cloS'\ned he will be found at home with his\nhappy little family. If there were\nmore saloons conducted on the -same\nplan as Mr. Farl conducts his busi\nness there would be much less ob\njection to the saloon in this state.\nIt might also be added that Mr.\nFarl is a strict temperance man\u2014but\nnot a prohibitionist.\n:u. v'.%\nSaturday News Re\nceives a et\nVermillion. Republican: The Wa\ntertown Saturday News Is sporting a\nmost eleganfciand effe\u00ab$ve ^ditprlal\npage these .s^winter.^^j^^^^oa't'\nknow as \"sporting\" Is the mort elegant\nexpression to use in thi| connection,\nbut it more or less effectively express-\n28.,\u2014 The Souths es the opinion held by ub that the Sat\nmaking railroads liable urday- News is a newspaper of which\nWatertown nyiy well be proud.\nH. A) Hanten has purchased a new\nWILL FIX\nTHERATES\nDakota Central Telephone\nCompany Hat Agreed to Set*\ntie Rate by Arbitration.\nCLYDE REED AND JOHN M00DIE\nTwo Prominent Local Merchants\nwill Act on Board and Choose\nThird Arbatrator.\nThe city commissioners! '*4nd the\nDakuta Central Telepcone company\nhave agreed to settle the rate to be\ncharged for the new automatic tele\nphones in this city by arbitration.\nThe telephone company selected\nJohn Moodie an dthe commissioners\nhave selected Clyde Reed, and the two\nmen will Belect a third man who will\nbe a civil engineer from outside the\nstate who Is familiar with the cost of\nthe construction of telephone equip\nment and business.\nThe rate will be fixed as soon as\nthe arbitrators can get together and\ngo over the matter carefully.\nThis will no doubt prove the easiest\nand best way to settle the rate ques\ntion for both..the company and Its\npatrons.\nThe gentlemen -who have been chos\nen to arbitrate tho rate matter are\nmen of sound business judgment and\nbusiness integrity and there is no.\nquestion but the patrons as well as the\ncompany will be perfectly BatiBfied\nwith their findings In the matter.\nRemains of George\nWhalen Laid to Rest\nGeorge Whalen, a Watertown young\nman, di\u00abl v^rjf sudd^nte in Fran-1\nTELLS OF\nLONG TRIE\nntes an\n,iK,o \u00abn liiih Th afid cleaY the foot Dlrtyl\nYes, we Were Bure'dirf.y. \"Some days\nthe mud .was frozen hard and so\nrough it seemed the car must shake to\npieces. There'\"was but little (ravel,\nexcept by buggies, and the largest\n\neiseo, Cal., on \"iSnuftry 19th- The|\nyoung man left this city about a year!\nago for Portland, Oregon, where he\nremained until about, a month ago\nwhen he. went to San Francisco.\n\u2022\u2022He had'resided in Watertown since\nwnu\nhis early childhood and upon the.\ndeath of his inother when he was bix\nyears old he went to live with his]\nfrom the high school several years,\nAOA ,TT\u00ab J!.J M/,1 fnHl *AMr I\nago. He did not feel very well for\nthe past couple of yearB and he thot\nit would be a benefit to his he^h td\nBeek a milder climate. jt.1\nMr. and Mrs. O'Henrn received\npostal card from him juat a week be-'\nfore he died and he said he would\nbe home shortly. They had no in\ntimation that he was ill at the time he\nwrote the card. Just a week from the\ntime they received the postal card\nthey received a telegram from the\nKnights of Columbus lodge at San\nFrancisco that he was dead.\nOeorge Whalen was a splendid man*\nquiet and unassuming, manly and a\ngentleman at all times and 'was loved\nand respected by all who knew him.\nHis death is a severe shock to Mr.\nand Mrs. O'Hearn as they have no\nchildren of their own and they re\ngarded George as near and dear to\nthem as their own son.\nHe was twenty-four years old at\nthe time of his death and a member\nof tbe local lodge of Knights of Col\numbus.\nThe deceased leaves his father,\nJohn Whalen, who ia employed on the\nNorthwestern, bis uncle, Robert\nO'Hearn, a brother Mathew, and four\nsisters, Miss Minnie, Mrs. J. B. Dore,\nMrs. John Lynch and Mrs. John Web\nBter, all residing in this city.\nThe funeral service Was held Mon\nday .morning at 9 o'clock at the Im\nmaculate Conception church and the\nKnight* of Columbus attended in a\nbody,\nenclosed runabout Studebaker car.) said that Krlsman carrie